	Document(content="Question: Can someone explain why they multiply the probabilities for two classes but not for class B? Answer: This solution has two errors. Firstly, class B should also multiply the two probabilities (1/15)*(2/15). Secondly, since this is an example of multinomial naive Bayes, all products of probabilities in the last column should also be multiplied by 2 (because in a bag-of-words model, \'notice lunch\' and \'lunch notice\' are represented using the same vector). However, we\'d give you most of the credit if you missed this last point.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'S24 Q4', 'timestamp': '2024-12-13T03:10:16Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 132}),
	Document(content="Question: Hi, my exam average is over 100 but it is capped at 100 on brightspace, for final grade calculation can my exam average be over 100? Answer: Yes, the part exceeding 100 will be counted while calculating the final score.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'exam grade cap?', 'timestamp': '2024-12-13T02:05:31Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 163}),
