	Document(content="Question: This problem just specifies GD, which I interpret as the batch formula in the Neural net slides. I don\'t understand how the summing part of the formula works here (obviously not in play on this problem) as there weren\'t any examples in the slides. Answer: batch GD kinda embodies the exact principle behind GD with nothing else fancy going on. In the update expression we calculate the total gradient over all $$n$$ data points, which just tells us in which direction the weights should remove to reduce loss. The $$\alpha$$ coef. is the 'learning rate,' or how aggressively we want to move towards the minimum. Of course we want the geometry of the loss function to correspond to the same scale of our weights, so we take the average/expectation by tacking the $$1/n$$ on.edit: why do we subtract this sum? Think how the loss function has to be convex, and which direction the gradient at any non-extrema point would point.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'GD vs SGD on fall 2022 6B', 'timestamp': '2024-12-13T01:18:15Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 135}),
	Document(content="Question: How do we solve this without having a calculator? Answer: $$-(-4+1.5\cdot 3.0) = -(0.5)$$ then apply the hint", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'F23 Exam 3 Q5A', 'timestamp': '2024-12-13T00:42:23Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 135}),
	Document(content="Question: Why in the slides is it a +ùõº ‚àó ùõø ‚àó ùë• but on all the exam solutions its -ùõº ‚àó ùõø ‚àó ùë•? Answer: I think it should be addition; error in solution", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 3 S24 Q6B', 'timestamp': '2024-12-13T00:38:36Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 126}),
	Document(content="Question: The answer key says E is the correct answer. Is this due to the fact that having 10 components in the model allows the model to better fit the data kind of like fitting a lower polynomial dataset with a higher order polynomial?¬† Answer: yeah if you look at the log-likelihood expression, it's monotonically non-decreasing over the number of mixture components. so as you said, you can attain lower error at the risk of overfitting (there's no penalty for model complexity)", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2023 3A', 'timestamp': '2024-12-12T23:31:09Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 135}),
