	Document(content="Question: The answer key for Exam 3 Spring2024 has different 4B, and 5A has no answer. Could this be fixed? Or check our answers below:4B) \'best price guarantee\' and \'final notice account\' are in class S, so with laplace smoothing P(\'price\'|S)=(1+1)/(6+12) = 1/95A) Logistic regression is used for classification because we set a threshold that will turn our output to 0 or 1, but it is also regression because it is just modified linear regression, and we are modelling the relationship between the variables to output some continuous probability that eventually turns into a 0 or 1. So its both classification and regression? But if the question is asking how we are using it, we are using it to classify whether someone enrolled in a wellness program or not, so it is just classificationplz help :( Answer: I also got 1/9 for question 4B. Not a TA so I can\'t confirm it\'s right, but someone else got your answer.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2024 missing problems?', 'timestamp': '2024-12-12T21:53:47Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 11, 'views': 144}),
	Document(content="Question: The information for this exam really isn\'t making much sense and the solutions to the past exams don\'t help me too much. Are there any office hours today or tomorrow before the exam? Answer: @385 I believe we don\'t have office hours for the final week. But you can always post your questions on Piazza : )", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Office Hours Before Exam 3?', 'timestamp': '2024-12-12T20:45:49Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 126}),
	Document(content="Question: For this question I do not understand how they got the value of the delta0 to be -1/4. Could someone please help me out? Thanks!! Answer: The first step for $$\delta_0$$ is directly from the equation above it. After that, you calculate $$w^Tx$$ and substitute it in the equation. Here, $$w^Tx=1*2+2*2-3*2=0$$. $$f$$ is sigmoid function and its value at $$0$$ is $$\frac{1}{2}$$ so $$f(0)=\frac{1}{2}$$. Substituting that in the equation you get $$-\frac{1}{4}$$.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Exam 3', 'timestamp': '2024-12-12T19:54:31Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 134}),
	Document(content="Question: Can anyone please explain how to get distance to B, C, and E? I thought the distance to B should be 3, to C is 4, and to E is 2.¬† Answer: I think this is just a typo or a mistake in the key. 3, 4, 2 seems correct.¬†", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'F23 exam 3 question 2 part A 1', 'timestamp': '2024-12-12T17:18:36Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 138}),
	Document(content="Question: I am confused where the (1-0.5) comes from in the solution. Is that the partial derivative of the log likelihood of B^t? Also, why is it multiplied by 0 for B_1^(t+1).Also, wouldn\'t only the first two responses satisfy the requirements of the question since it only asks for the updated B_1 and B_0? Answer: To answer your first question, the (1-0.5) comes from the gradient ascent update formula. To update parameters using gradient descent, we can use B_j (new) = B_j(old) + a(y-y_hat)x_j where a is your step size, B_j is your coefficient, and x_j is your datapoint. Recall this formula for y_hat where y_hatKnowing this, find the value of yhat from the coefficients given in part a. This is where the 0.5 comes from. Then with the given value of y, we have 1 - 0.5. For your other question, I believe you are right since the question only asks for B_0 and B_1.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'F2022 Exam Question 4C', 'timestamp': '2024-12-12T16:38:18Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 131}),
