	Document(content="Question: I am working on the mini project for path 1, and have descended into a rabbit hole of confusion for all 3 questions.The first question which can be paraphrased \'is it possible to naturally cluster the students\' I have been led to that the answer is just straight up no. Using KMeans for a range of n_clusters= 1 to 25 and printing out the number of students in each cluster for each clusters results in there always being clusters with thousands of students and some with only 1-5. Below is shown the output for n_clusters=11 (I print out all 0-24 in my actual program).-------Evaluating kmeans in cluster 11---------Number of students in cluster 0 of 10 is 10270Number of students in cluster 1 of 10 is 1Number of students in cluster 2 of 10 is 2621Number of students in cluster 3 of 10 is 7Number of students in cluster 4 of 10 is 7Number of students in cluster 5 of 10 is 1Number of students in cluster 6 of 10 is 4Number of students in cluster 7 of 10 is 332Number of students in cluster 8 of 10 is 394Number of students in cluster 9 of 10 is 6Number of students in cluster 10 of 10 is 29I researched into other methods and found the elbow method and also PCA plotting, and the elbow method indicates a strong k-value in the range of like 8-12, which seems really high to me, and this leads to when I make a PCA plot, A lot of the clusters overlap heavily on it, and there really doesn\'t seem to be a good k-value for the clusters. I\'ve tried lower values but it just ends up with nearly all (thousands) of the students in one cluster and then like 1-50 in the other(s). I\'ve reviewed my code pretty thoroughly and am pretty sure I\'ve done everything right. I am standardizing my data (using StandardScaler), then using KMeans to be applied to my filtered (watched >= 5 videos) students using fit_predict on the standardized data for each iteration.For question 2 (paraphrased \'can we predict mean value of a students score across all videos\'), I initially thought to use a logistic regression, before realizing logistic regressions only apply to binary values, so I cannot use it since a mean score is on a range [0, 1], so this leaves a linear regression and ridge regression. In the slides it mentions ridge regression is better for data with many features, and considering that I am using 7-10 features (I\'ve been playing with that a lot too), I figured ridge regression would be good. However, after running cross-validation in order to get the best lambda/regularization parameter (or alpha in Python), and using it on ridge regression my ridge regression ends up with an r^2 value of 0.035, which is absolutely atrocious. This led me to try linear regression, but that had similar results. So do I just show all my data and say that there is no correlation?Finally, question 3 (paraphrased \'for each video can we predict what a student will score on that video\'), I am using a logistic regression since it is binary, either they score 0 or 1. I repeat for every video_id: split the data into the feature matrix and output / scores / target for that video and then train test split and then fit the logistic regression and check the accuracy score. This one actually has pretty decent results, which I am checking by outputting the accuracy score for all 93 videos. Most videos fall in the range of 60-80% accuracy score, with some outliers. This one not as confused about but just making sure that this logic is what the question wants to see.Do these results sound about right? I can share my code if necessary, or screenshots of the graphs. Answer: I prefer not telling you the results are right or wrong. First, the questions are open questions. Second, to ensure the fairness among the class, I prefer not revealing the preference on your results.¬†However, I could ask some questions as a peer in your class. I think there is one question to be answered. Since your model\'s performance is not high, does that mean the features have no correlation or your model is not good enough to capture them? For example, if I increase the complexity of the model, will it increase the performance?¬†Note that your report is expected to have conclusions with your reasons and evidence to support.¬†", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Mini Project Path 1 Logic / Results', 'timestamp': '2024-12-06T03:53:49Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 9}),
