	Document(content="Question: For the third patter, I\'m somewhat confused as to how Regex handles overlapping. So my assumption is that [a-z]+ would match with all of \'darthvader\' since its greedy. Then, it won\'t match anything for [0-9]*, which is fine. But for [a-zA-Z\-], is it still able to match with \'darthvader\'? If so, why - shouldn\'t it start trying to match with \'@\' since [a-z]+ has already used \'darthvader\'? Is there some backtracking element which allows it to match? Thanks! Answer: Very subtle question! We did not go into details of the regex engine and its translation to finite-state automata, which would explain the underlying implementation. A regex quantifier like + is inherently greedy as you point out, but also *docile*. This means that the engine will match as much as possible, but if this results in the rest of the regex being unable to match the string, the engine will indeed backtrack (usually one character at a time) to have the full regex match some part of the string.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Question about Regex overlapping', 'timestamp': '2024-11-17T20:37:46Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 122}),
