	Document(content="Question: Hi, I\'m getting these errors, and I can\'t figure out why they are occurring because I think that my code is right, but I keep getting these. I know this is a bit of a late post, but I would appreciate if you could take a look at it and see if you can find out what\'s wrong because it\'s due tonight, and I don\'t want to blindly submit this last part and possibly get points off of the homework because of it. I\'ve attached both the error, and the code for the function below. Thanks a lot.Screenshot_2024-11-15_185301.png Answer: Check @295. Let me know if the error persists.", meta={'folders': ['hw9'], 'title': 'gmm.py', 'timestamp': '2024-11-15T23:59:09Z', 'user': 'lx4qmyhoo44c5', 'tags': ['hw9', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 11}),
	Document(content="Question: Why is $$Z_{96}$$ 2.05 and not 1.75 here?![Screenshot_2024-11-14_at_21.45.24.png](/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&prefix=paste%2Fm01d2lo8dhi1kd%2Fc25ba5ee4522fd629985f4ac08bf2547c9420ce96db81950f18a070e1ce47cdd%2FScreenshot_2024-11-14_at_21.45.24.png) Answer: For a two-sided confidence interval, you need to find the z-value so that the area (or probability mass) over the interval (-z,z) is 0.96. But the table shows areas over the interval (-infinity,z). Since the area over the interval (-z,z) is 0.96, the area over the two tails (i.e., (z, infinity) and (-infinity,-z)) are 0.02 each by symmetry of the Gaussian. So, if we found the z-value such that the area over (-infinity,z) is 0.96 + 0.02 = 0.98, then the area over the interval (-z,z) would be 0.96 as desired. This is why we choose z = 2.05 instead of z = 1.75.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2022 Confidence Interval', 'timestamp': '2024-11-15T02:47:38Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 136}),
	Document(content="Question: I have a question for why the answer to question 2 part B in Fall 2022 exam 2 is what it is. It is asking to select which regexes provide a \'valid match\' to the strings [darthvader@sithschool.edu, r2-d2@droidtech.edu,¬†lastnameYoda@jedi.edu]. One of the correct answers was [a-z]+[0-9]*[a-zA-Z\-]+[2]?@[a-zA-Z]+[\.edu] , which doesn\'t give a match to the entire string, but does match the emails up the period. Is this a correct answer because \'valid match\' means it matches something in the string, even if it isn\'t the whole string, or is this an error in the answer key? Answer: The question writer in this case was likely asking whether the \'match()\' method would return something other than None. With this interpretation, the answer is correct, because the match() method does not need to match the whole string (unless we have ^ and $ at the front and back of the regex, respectively).¬†", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Question about Fall 2022 Exam 2 Question 2', 'timestamp': '2024-11-14T21:46:50Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 124}),
	Document(content="Question: In kmeans.py, we are asked to find the closest cluster to each point to assign the point to that cluster, but in Point, the distFrom function calculates the distance between two Points which is called in the closest function. The closest function says it can take a Cluster or a Point object, but the distFrom function only works with Points. Should we specify if a Cluster object is passed in to use its center attribute in distFrom, and if so, where? Answer: You don\'t need to specify anything differently if a Cluster object is passed to distFrom. Look for the common attribute/property between Point class and Cluster class which resembles the coordinates of a point and use that to calculate distance.", meta={'folders': ['hw9'], 'title': 'Cluster\'s Center', 'timestamp': '2024-11-14T07:20:43Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw9', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 147}),
