	Document(content="Question: I am getting the following error, is this an issue with my test calls, or should i be calling idf[0:10]? also, are we allowed to use collections for problem 2?*** Testing build_idf_matrix ***Traceback (most recent call last):¬† ¬† print(idf[0][0:10])IndexError: invalid index to scalar variable.Here is my test section in main for step 2:print(\'\n*** Testing build_tf_matrix ***\')tf = build_tf_matrix(docword)print(tf[0][0:10])print(tf[1][0:10])print(tf.sum(axis=1))print(\'\n*** Testing build_idf_matrix ***\')idf = build_idf_matrix(docword)print(idf[0][0:10])print(\'\n*** Testing build_tfidf_matrix ***\')tfidf = build_tfidf_matrix(docword)print(tfidf.shape)print(tfidf[0][0:10])print(tfidf[1][0:10]) Answer: @244", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'step 2 index to scalar variable error', 'timestamp': '2024-11-04T01:32:35Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 114}),
	Document(content="Question: I keep having trouble while building my doc_word matrix. I have the matrix being filled out by a series of for-loops, and then the counter for each ngram iterating through each document in order to find how many occurrences of the ngram there is. This method proves to take too long to load, and I have been unable to see the results of the calculation yet. Is there a better method that you recommend going about this portion? Since I must be taking an incorrect approach if it is taking this long to run. Answer: The logic of building the word doc is:1.¬†Prepare Text Documents: Each document is read, cleaned, and then split into smaller word segments (called n-grams), based on a specified number of words. These n-grams are unique combinations of consecutive words from each document.2.¬†Create a Unique Word Segment List: After generating n-grams from all documents, we collect all unique n-grams and arrange them in a sorted list. This unique list will be used to track the presence and frequency of each n-gram in every document.3,¬†Build a Document-Word Matrix: We create a matrix where each row represents a document, and each column corresponds to a unique n-gram from the list. The matrix counts how often each n-gram appears in each document.4.¬†Normalize the Matrix: Optionally, we can adjust the counts in each document\'s row so they represent relative frequencies instead of raw counts. This step involves dividing each count by the total number of n-grams in that document, so each entry reflects a proportion of that document\'s n-grams. This makes comparisons across documents easier.A quick note to your debugging, you can print out each length of the list/cleaned words to see which step is going wrong.¬†", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'HW8 Problem 2', 'timestamp': '2024-11-03T22:28:23Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 134}),
