	Document(content="Question: Is the document cleaning function supposed to return a string with no spaces at all? I\'m having a difficult time figuring out how to iterate through a string with no spaces to find ngram occurrences for the bag-of-words step. Answer: The bag of words are the ngrams so it doesn\'t matter if there are spaces because ngrams for this assignment are character based, you just take every n characters. This removes the possibility of an ngram having a space in it.", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'Homework 8, Problem 2 cleaning function', 'timestamp': '2024-11-03T14:50:19Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 125}),
	Document(content="Question: I am getting stuck on how to fix my matrix builder for part 1 of this part of the homework. I don\'t understand why it\'s causing a huge list of n-grams to output. The photo is the output of my function.¬†def build_doc_word_matrix(doclist, n, normalize=False):¬† ¬†¬† ¬† \'\'\'¬† ¬† Arguments:¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† doclist: list of strings, each string is the name of a file to be read.¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† n: int, the length of each n-gram¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† normalize: boolean, whether to normalize the doc-word matrix¬† ¬† Returns:¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† docword: 2-dimensional numpy array, the doc-word matrix for the cleaned documents,¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† with one row per document and one column per ngram (there should be as many columns as unique words that appear across *all* documents.¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† Also, Before constructing the doc-word matrix, you should sort the list of ngrams output and construct the doc-word matrix based on the sorted list¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ngramlist: list of strings, the list of ngrams that correspond to the columns in docword¬† ¬† \'\'\'¬† ¬† # TODO: complete the function¬† ¬† docword, ngramlist = None, list()¬† ¬† # 1. Create the cleaned string for each doc (use read_and_clean_doc)¬† ¬† clean_lists = []¬† ¬† for i in doclist: #itterating throguh the list of strings and cleaning each one¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† cleaned_list = read_and_clean_doc(i)¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† clean_lists.append(cleaned_list)¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† #append the cleaned_list to clean_lists¬† ¬† # 2. Create and use ngram lists to build the doc word matrix¬† ¬† #call function pass in cleand_list and n¬† ¬†¬† ¬† for i in clean_lists:¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† x = get_ngrams(i ,n)¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ngramlist.append(x)¬† ¬†¬† ¬† #doclist is the row¬† ¬† #ngramlist is the column¬† ¬† #numpy 2d array¬† ¬† #length_ngram = len(ngramlist)¬† ¬† #length_doclist = len(doclist)¬† ¬† #this is getting the size of the matrix¬† ¬† #its in the correct form of rows and columns¬† ¬† union_ngrams = []¬† ¬† union_ngrams = set()¬† ¬† for i in ngramlist:¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† union_ngrams.update(list(i))¬† ¬† union_ngrams = sorted(list(union_ngrams))¬† ¬† length_ngram = len(union_ngrams)¬† ¬† length_doclist = len(doclist)¬† ¬† docword = np.zeros([length_doclist, length_ngram])¬† ¬† holder = []¬† ¬† for i in doclist:¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† cleaner = read_and_clean_doc(i)¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† holder.append(cleaner)¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† z = get_ngrams(holder, n)¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† for l in z:¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† docword[doclist.index(i)][union_ngrams.index(l)]¬† ¬† #Now we need to itterate¬† ¬† #docword = np.array([[ngramlist],[doclist]])¬† ¬† return docword, ngramlist Answer: It\'s hard for instructors to directly debug for you. However, let me describe the logic:1. Prepare Text Documents: Each document is read, cleaned, and then split into smaller word segments (called n-grams), based on a specified number of words. These n-grams are unique combinations of consecutive words from each document.2. Create a Unique Word Segment List: After generating n-grams from all documents, we collect all unique n-grams and arrange them in a sorted list. This unique list will be used to track the presence and frequency of each n-gram in every document.3, Build a Document-Word Matrix: We create a matrix where each row represents a document, and each column corresponds to a unique n-gram from the list. The matrix counts how often each n-gram appears in each document.4. Normalize the Matrix: Optionally, we can adjust the counts in each document\'s row so they represent relative frequencies instead of raw counts. This step involves dividing each count by the total number of n-grams in that document, so each entry reflects a proportion of that document\'s n-grams. This makes comparisons across documents easier.Some notes to your debugging, you can print out each length of the list/cleaned words to see which step is going wrong.¬†", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'Stuck on step 1 of Hw8_2.py', 'timestamp': '2024-11-03T02:05:05Z', 'user': 'lqwr69lt6y3rb', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 9}),
