	Document(content="Question: Just wanted to confirm something real quick. The arrangement of rig,ight and righ in top 10 common n-grams in english.txt output should be {\' rig\':54,\'ight\':54,\'righ\':54} instead of {\'righ\':54,\'ight\':54,\' rig\':54} right? Answer: According to a TA in office hours the order is {\' rig\': 54, \'ight\': 54, \'righ\': 54}. The important thing to note here is rig is actually \' rig\' with a space at the beginning giving it a higher order than the letter i. This part was understandably confusing, but in Unicode space comes before most characters (control characters come before but you wouldn\'t see those so much) so strings with spaces will come before any letter.", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'HW 8 problem 1', 'timestamp': '2024-11-01T22:58:51Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 131}),
	Document(content="Question: For all those struggling with final outputs for Problem 2 being slightly off although the rest of your values for all previous steps are correct: here is your answer.After spending way to much of my time in office hours trying to find what was wrong with my \'find_distinctive_words\' function, I found that the \'argsort\' function varies across different machines. For example, I ran my code on my Windows laptop and got the output:{\'lecs\\1_vidText.txt\': [\'econ\', \'seco\', \'rsec\'], \'lecs\\2_vidText.txt\': [\'uter\', \'poin\', \'sspo\']}.I ran the exact same code on Linux on one of the lab computers and got the README output. I was told the autograder is run on Linux so for those running your code on any other systems, if you want to see what the autograder will see, try running your code on Linux first.If you are still not getting the README output, the second thing you need to do is to slightly adjust your tfidf before sorting it with argsort. You have to multiply each element by -1. This can be easily implemented (tfidf = -tfidf). Then sort it via argsort and you can find your largest 3 words by index [0,1,2].Note: Leave the sorting method as default (eg. Don\'t use kind = \'mergesort/heapsort/stable/etc\')Hope that helps!Leave any questions that this post doesn\'t clarify and I\'ll try my best to answer them. Answer: There are multiple ngrams with the same frequency. So while grading, I hope that all possible combinations are graded favorably.", meta={'folders': ['hw8'], 'title': 'Solution to Incorrect Final Outputs (HW8 Problem2)!!', 'timestamp': '2024-11-01T16:16:52Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw8', 'student'], 'likes': 3, 'views': 149}),
