	Document(content="Note: Hello everyone,The grades for Homework 6 have been released for all sections on Brightspace and Github. You can see your grading feedback in the Homework 6 repository on GitHub. To access your feedback, please follow these steps:Go to your Homework 6 repository on GitHub.Click on the drop-down menu under \'main\'.Select \'Tags\'.Click on \'graded-update\'.You will find a file named \'grading_output.txt\' in your repository. This file contains the output of the grading script, detailing which test cases you passed and their respective point values. Please note that we typically grade homework assignments using various test cases. Your code was run against several test cases, which you can see in the \'grading_output.txt\' file. Points are awarded based on the test cases your code successfully completes. The point value of each test case varies according to its difficulty level.If some test cases are missing in grading_output.txt or if the file is incomplete/empty, please submit a regrade request following the steps below.If you believe there is an error in your grade, such as a score discrepancy between your GitHub score and Brightspace score or an approved homework extension that hasn\'t been accounted for, please submit a regrade request to ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com. You have one week from the day the grades are posted on Brightspace to submit this request. When sending your regrade request, please ensure you include:A link to your GitHub repository (essential for homework assignments).Section Number.Grading item (e.g., Homework 6).Purdue email address (if the email isn\'t sent from a Purdue account).Detailed reasoning or justification for the regrade, specifically referencing the README.For regrade requests, please adhere to the following guidelines:Send a separate email for each homework.Use the subject line: \'HW# regrade request\'.Important: The regrade request emails not obeying the above instructions will be ignored.", meta={'folders': ['hw6'], 'title': 'Homework 6 Grades Released', 'timestamp': '2024-10-18T02:44:54Z', 'user': 'lzx17up0ze624m', 'tags': ['hw6', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 124}),
	Document(content="Question: Is the feature_matrix function asking for us to calculate each sample value raise to each degree, or is it asking for us to calculate something else? The directions in the skeleton code have confused me, and I\'ve not gotten correct values later on in the code when raising each value to the certain degrees, and I\'m not sure whether I calculated something wrong or I did the wrong thing for the feature_matrix function. In addition, where do the target y values come from for the least sqaures function when calling it in the main? Thanks Answer: Please see post @204", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Feature_Matrix function', 'timestamp': '2024-10-17T14:16:06Z', 'user': 'lx4qmyhoo44c5', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 13}),
	Document(content="Question: I\'m not getting the correct values for y_hat x_2 and x_4, and I think the problem is in the feature_matrix function, because I know my least squares should be right. I would go to office hours, but I don\'t have any time this week, so this is the best I can do. I just need some starting point for that function because I don\'t necessarily understand what is supposed to be calculated through it. Thanks Answer: The input to the function is a list of sample values, which we\'ll denote by $$ \textbf{x} $$, and your task is to convert this list into a feature matrix, denoted by $$ \textbf{X} $$, up to a specified degree $$ d $$.Here\'s how the transformation should look:$$ \textbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} x_{1}\\ x_{2}\\ \vdots\\ x_{N} \end{bmatrix} \rightarrow \textbf{X} = \begin{bmatrix} x_{1}^{d} & x_{1}^{d-1} & \dots & x_{1}^{1} & 1 \\ x_{2}^{d} & x_{2}^{d-1} & \dots & x_{2}^{1} & 1 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots \\ x_{N}^{d} & x_{N}^{d-1} & \dots & x_{N}^{1} & 1 \end{bmatrix} $$In other words, for each sample $$ x_i $$, you\'ll create a row in $$ \textbf{X} $$ containing the powers of $$ x_i $$ from $$ d $$ down to $$ 0¬†$$, with the final column as $$ 1 $$ to represent $$ x_i^0 $$.The instructions provided in the function skeleton outline this structure. To implement this, consider using a loop or a list comprehension to generate the matrix (in the form of a nested list). Both approaches can efficiently convert the list of values into the required feature matrix format.", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Feature Matrix', 'timestamp': '2024-10-17T00:01:59Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 15}),
	Document(content="Question: May I know why the CDF isn\'t a step function? According to lecture slide, a discrete CDF will have a graph sort of like a step and a continuous CDF will have a continuous graph. I guess my question is from the question how do we know if its discrete or continuous? Answer: The question asks you to plot the CDF for the given PDF so the CDF will be continuous. If a PMF was given instead, then it would be a discrete CDF. Edit: Marks have been awarded if the correct graph is plotted based on reasonable PMF assumptions.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'exam 1 Question 3 part B', 'timestamp': '2024-10-15T02:42:59Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 140}),
