	Document(content="Question: I used a different method to calculate the minimum sample size without a loop and it supposedly yielded a result that was off by one from the actual answer. I used the equations in the image below which were found in the \'hypothesis\' slides. Would this be a viable solution, or would I need to change it to the loop solution to avoid losing points? Answer: If it matches the answer, then use whatever method you like. However, you may find it easier to implement with the loop method as your z score is always updating.", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Minimum sample size calculation', 'timestamp': '2024-09-27T23:52:08Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 101}),
	Document(content="Question: I went to office hours and the UTA who helped said my code was correct but the mean output wasn\'t. I\'d appreciate any feedback on how to fix this. I will link photos below. Answer: Make sure you\'re setting the degrees of freedom in your standard deviation calculation. You\'re also using the wrong population mean it should be 5 for 2.2.2.3 Think about how increasing the sample size would affect calculations for standard error, z-score, and p-value while you get to the significance level of 0.05.2.5 use the calculation in @135.", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'UTA Says Code is right by mean output is wrong.', 'timestamp': '2024-09-27T14:57:26Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 16}),
	Document(content="Question: I have two questions related to these two and the z-score formula.1. Is the formula for z-score (xÃÑ - Œº)/SE or (xÃÑ-Œº)/œÉ ? The number of standard deviations away from the mean or the number of standard errors away from the mean?The slides show the first, which is different from what I learned in a previous stats class and from other online resources.compared to¬† ¬†2. What does a and b in ùí©(a,b) represent? In the first slide below, it is N(population mean, SE), but in the second it is N(population mean, SE^2) Answer: The z-score formula is (xÀâ‚àíŒº)/œÉ¬†when comparing an individual data point to the population mean using standard deviation œÉ, but it becomes (xÀâ‚àíŒº)/SE¬†when comparing a sample mean to the population mean using standard error.In ùí©(a, b), a¬†represents the mean, and b¬†can represent either the variance (œÉ¬≤ or SE¬≤) or the standard deviation (œÉ or SE), depending on the context.", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Confusion over Standard Deviation (œÉ) and Standard Error (SE)', 'timestamp': '2024-09-27T05:21:33Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 123}),
	Document(content="Question: For part 2, I got a p-value of around 1, is that correct or did I make a horrible error? And for part 3, how are you supposed to find the minimum sample size? I looked through the notes and slides and couldn\'t find anything relating to this. I looked up a possible solution with using the margin of error, and using the new z score and standard deviation to calculate the minimum population, but I end up with the original population. Any help would be appreciated, thanks! Answer: For part 2, a p-value near 1 suggests an error‚Äîdouble-check your sample size, mean, and standard error, then recalculate the z-score and p-value using the correct formulas from the slides.¬†For part 3, think about how increasing the sample size would affect calculations for standard error, z-score, and p-value while you get to the significance level of 0.05.", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Q2 Part 2 and 3', 'timestamp': '2024-09-27T04:01:03Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 122}),
	Document(content="Question: I uploaded the pdf to the git but when I try to preview the pdf it says \'error rendering embedded code\'. Do I need to be able to successfully preview the pdf on git for the submission to count?20875_img_pdf.png Answer: Correct. I\'d recommend using a PDF editor or saving it as a doc, then saving it as a PDF. Make sure to be able to read it before submitting it.", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'PDF for HW05', 'timestamp': '2024-09-27T03:35:14Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 124}),
