	Document(content="Note: Hello all,The grades for Homework 2 have been released for all sections on Brightspace and Github. You can see your grading feedback in the Homework 2 repository on GitHub. To access your feedback, please follow these steps:Go to your Homework 2 repository on GitHub.Click on the drop-down menu under \'main\'.Select \'Tags\'.Click on \'graded-update\'.You will find a file named \'grading_output.txt\' in your repository. This file contains the output of the grading script, detailing which test cases you passed and their respective point values. Please refer to the attached picture for visual guidance in @70.Also, note that some of you might forked multiple times, which may result as the following snapshot:I have manually merged these repos and please find your grading and submission in \'homework-2-f24-username\'Please note that we typically grade homework assignments using various test cases. Your code was run against several test cases, which you can see in the \'grading_output.txt\' file. Points are awarded based on the test cases your code successfully completes. The point value of each test case varies according to its difficulty level.If you believe there is an error in your grade, such as a score discrepancy between GitHub score and Brightspace score or an approved homework extension that hasn\'t been accounted for, please submit a regrade request to ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com. You have one week from the day the grades are posted on Brightspace to submit this request. When sending your regrade request, please ensure you include:A link to your GitHub repository (essential for homework assignments).Section Number.Grading item (e.g., Homework 1).Purdue email address (if the email isn\'t sent from a Purdue account).Detailed reasoning or justification for the regrade, specifically referencing the README.For regrade requests, please adhere to the following guidelines:Send a separate email for each homework.Use the subject line: \'HW# regrade request\'.Important: The regrade request emails not obeying the above instructions will be ignored.As always, if you have any additional questions, please don\'t hesitate to post them on Piazza.", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Homework 2 Grades Released!', 'timestamp': '2024-09-15T16:17:09Z', 'user': 'jc6jsfzirna1eu', 'tags': ['hw2', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 127}),
	Document(content="Question: I keep getting an error saying \'ModuleNotFoundError: No module named \'matplotlib\'\' for both matplotlib and numpy whenever I try to run my code. I tried uninstalling and reinstailling it and it still does not work. How do I go about fixing this error? Answer: Make sure that you are using the correct environment for running the code. There are multiple ways you can check from the terminal, like pip list or which python3¬†If you are using conda, you can use conda info --envs.¬†", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Module not found error', 'timestamp': '2024-09-13T23:59:06Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 94}),
