	Document(content="Question: Professor Makur asked me to post this.¬†On HW 01, I did not earn points on either question. When I went through the grading report, it says the error was \'\'type\' object is not subscriptable\'. However, the code runs locally without errors. I looked up the possible causes for the error and chatGPT says it could be related to type hinting.Could you please help me resolve this issue? Answer: Vineet, please make a formal regrade request as well before the regrade deadline. @Gaurav Patel , @Kanika Gandhi , @Tianchun Li , please take a look at this. Type hints should not affect how code runs in principle.", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'HW01 Grading', 'timestamp': '2024-09-13T19:30:58Z', 'user': 'lr2rya6jfgtmq', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 14}),
	Document(content="Question: I have been using the prompt line python3 -mpip install --user scipy and I am getting this error and don\'t know what to do. Answer: It seems you\'ve ran into an exceptionally unique error! As a stopgap solution you can always use a google colab notebook to run your code in a pinch. It should automatically import anything your file needs.As for solving this issue try updating pip throughpython -m pip install --upgrade pipYou can also try to upgrade the version of CMake installed. It is probably installed through pip unless you previously installed it, in which case that version might be causing issues.If it is installed under pip (you can check this with \'python -m pip list\') you can remove it withpython -m pip uninstall cmaketo get a fresh install of it when you try to re-install scipy.Cmake could also be installed under VSCode\'s extensions, if that is the case try removing/disabling it and seeing if that changes the install error.", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Homework 3', 'timestamp': '2024-09-13T19:28:47Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 98}),
	Document(content="Question: Does anyone understand how we are supposed to do the stats.probplot function for this problem specifically? Or like where I can look to see how we are supposed to use it?Also if I don‚Äôt manage to get that part working as I going to be counted off for everything in that question as that part is pretty much required to be able to do the rest? Answer: I recommend looking at the documentation for the function, it'll tell you the various parameters and what the function returns: https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.stats.probplot.htmlIn this case we have to pass in the data and the distribution type.", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Stats.probplot', 'timestamp': '2024-09-13T18:16:22Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 84}),
	Document(content="Question: Does anyone know if for sweep_n if we are supposed to find the number of bins needed as well as the bin_width based off the values we have and then the number of bins wanted are then plug those into the compute_j function we made previously.¬†Are we even supposed to find the bin_width or just use bin_number?¬†Are we supposed to use same equation as what was in compute_j?Im just very confused Answer: For each bin number (n) value between min_bins and max_bins, you need to calculate the corresponding bin width and use that as input for the compute_j function.", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Sweep_n', 'timestamp': '2024-09-13T18:10:28Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 76}),
