	Document(content="Question: So, when working on this part of the question, I have managed to be able to figure out the correct amount of bin numbers and then converted that into the bin width, made sure to process the raw data. I then calculated the ro (compute_j) within the function just to be able to test what the outcome is as a list.I just had two questions: 1: If we are supposed to run it into the compute_j function and if so how would we be able to get a list from the float output?2: I\'m doing what was above in compute_j just in the sweep_n function instead, yet I don\'t get numbers that match up with what was given as the test output. I don\'t know what I\'m doing wrong for that.Sweep_n functioncompute_j functionoutput gotten Answer: For each bin number (n) value between min_bins and max_bins, you need to calculate the corresponding bin width and use that as input for the compute_j function. Make sure you don\'t normalize the data twice. Please attend the office hours for more help.", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Sweep_n Problem 1 HW3', 'timestamp': '2024-09-13T03:46:33Z', 'user': 'lzpvv2r8inv6y7', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 10}),
