	Document(content="Question: In my code, whenever I hit run on test case 1,this is my output: {1: [\'Bob\', 5, 1995, 29, (\'John\', 15, 1985, 39)], 2: (\'Jane\', 20, 1989, 35)}this is the expected output: {1: [(\'John\', 15, 1985, 39), (\'Bob\', 5, 1995, 29)], 2: (\'Jane\', 20, 1989, 35)}There should be a parenthesis around Bob and his info, but I can\'t seem to make \'Bob\' + info a list item itself rather than a simple list of values. How do I group \'Bob\' + info into 1 list item? I\'ve attached my code below. Answer: The square brackets mean that it is a list, which is what you\'re casting it into under your if statement. The datatype for parentheses is tuple.", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': '(In problem 2) How to get parenthesis when the dictionary value turns into a list', 'timestamp': '2024-09-06T20:13:10Z', 'user': 'm0cq1oy213ao', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 9}),
	Document(content="Question: to have the program run correctly, I understand that I need to copy and paste the testing code at the bottom of my program. For question 2, the testing code includes the statement \'print hist.\' Should I include that *in* my code, or completely leave it out? Do we submit our programs with a test case at the bottom? Answer: You don\'t need to include any testing code in your submission. Just the 2 main functions histogram and combine_birthday_data will suffice.", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'submission w/ or w/o test cases?', 'timestamp': '2024-09-06T13:28:40Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 114}),
	Document(content="Question: Hello,I\'ve been trying everything to get my code to run but I\'m not able to get it to work. I know 90% of it is right but I keep getting the same errors. Will I still get some credit if my code doesn\'t run or does it have to run to get any credit on homework?¬†Thank you. Answer: It has to run in order to get credit - feel free to stop by office hours and a TA can help debug any issues.", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Error Running Code', 'timestamp': '2024-09-05T22:20:01Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 12}),
	Document(content="Question: Here is the proof: Proof of Integral Answer: Marked as solved", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'Prof. Kocaoglu asked \'How do we solve the integral for Gaussian Distribution = 1?\'', 'timestamp': '2024-09-05T21:52:34Z', 'user': 'l8au6lxqxgg1yd', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 130}),
	Document(content="Question: For Part 2, does it matter in what order the keys of the output dictionary should show when printed?¬†For example, does it matter if my output is{1: [(\'John\', 15, 1985, 39), (\'Bob\', 5, 1995, 29)], 2: (\'Jane\', 20, 1989, 35)}or {2: (\'Jane\', 20, 1989, 35), 1: [(\'John\', 15, 1985, 39), (\'Bob\', 5, 1995, 29)]} ?I\'m having this question because I change the order of tuples in the input lists, the order of keys of output might change. Answer: First, the order of the key, i.e., the month of the person\'s birthday, will be the same order as the person_to_month. Second, the order of the people (value/tuple) given a key will also be in the same order sa the person_to_month.¬†For example:Suppose the person_to_month is [(\'Bob\', 5), (\'Alec\', 5), (\'Charlie\', 7)]The resulted dictionary will be:{¬† ¬† 5: [(\'Bob\', ......), (\'Alice\', ......)],¬† ¬† 7: [(\'Charlie\', ......)]}", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW2 Part 2 Output Dictionary Key Order Question', 'timestamp': '2024-09-05T21:00:05Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 122}),
