	Document(content="Question: I see all the people are in the same order in each dict in input, is this always the case? Answer: No, you should assume people will have different names and will appear in random orders.", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'problem 2 assumption', 'timestamp': '2024-08-30T22:00:00Z', 'user': 'jc6jsfzirna1eu', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 128}),
	Document(content="Question: For the provided .py files in the repository (which to my understanding were different than the test cases in the read me)¬† is there anywhere we can see if we get the expected output? Answer: The readme just provided some examples. The test files provided more cases to test.For the histogram, you could use your understanding to calculate the expected output yourself as there are just few numbers. Or you could use some library functions to further double check. For example, you can view some library function in here.¬†In the birthday case, the expected output is provided in the comments in the test case files.¬†", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW2 test case files', 'timestamp': '2024-08-30T21:18:24Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 117}),
	Document(content="Question: Can we use GitHub Desktop to push and commit our submission file? Answer: Yes you can.", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Using GitHub Desktop to Submit', 'timestamp': '2024-08-30T20:37:26Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 99}),
	Document(content="Question: I\'ve been trying for a while to learn how to use git to push my file and went through several tutorials, and the only time I got close, it said something about comparing and making a pull request. When I clicked that, it took me to the code but didn\'t show any options. I also edited the problems.py file to have my code, so that should still be visible. I\'m just not sure how to push properly. Answer: I am not sure what did you do specifically as I cannot see your actual files/error message. But, in general, you should always use \'git status\' to make sure that your local matches with the git repository before making any changes to local. Then, after making sure the local sync with git, then you should do add and push.¬†Follow this GitHub webpage for more information. You may need to do a force push, but be careful with this force push operation. It may flush the changes you made on git. For more information, follow this page. If you are not clear about the operations, you could join the office hour today for more help : )", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Git Pushed File not Showing', 'timestamp': '2024-08-30T20:26:26Z', 'user': 'm013fhxlz6a75q', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 95}),
	Document(content="Question: I edited the file in GITHUB and commited it from there. Does that work for a submission or do I need to do all the push stuff. When I look at my code in GITHUB its correct and done. I was just wondering if that works or not. Answer: As long as you can see your changes and they are committed successfully, it works.", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Git question', 'timestamp': '2024-08-30T18:49:58Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 94}),
	Document(content="Question: EDIT: Never mind. I now notice that the first bin\'s lower bound is NOT inclusive. I misunderstood.Below is a test case that is posted on the README. I am confused on why hist[0] is 0 and not 1 in this case. So we would end up switching max and min val since min > max.Then for hist[0] that would give us a lower bound of 0 and upper bound of 1 for that bin (since bin width would be 1). And since 0 is in this dataset why is it not counted in the first bin of the histogram?Also if you add up all of the frequencies in each bin you only get 7, but there are 8 valid values. EDIT: Never mind. I now notice that the first bin\'s lower bound is NOT inclusive. I misunderstood. Answer: Marked as solved.¬†", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW2 test cases', 'timestamp': '2024-08-30T17:07:20Z', 'user': 'ktnb58hevai12h', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 113}),
	Document(content="Question: I have watched the videos for how to complete the homework, but I am still having trouble understanding how to use all the different platforms like PyCharm, VSC, GitHub and how they all relate to each other and how to code within them and be able to run the code. So are there any other videos that will make it easier to understand how everything works?¬† Answer: PyCharm and VSCode are both IDEs. You can use either to complete the homework\'s you do not need both. I\'d personally suggest VSCode as it can also act as an IDE for other programming languages. GitHub is just for giving you the homework assignments and for you to \'submit\' the assignments. The only thing you need to worry about there is to pull the assignments from GitHub and push the assignment back to GitHub when you\'ve completed it. I\'m not sure I have any videos for you, but if you\'re still confused feel free to drop by office hours and a TA can walk you through it!", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Homework 1 Help.', 'timestamp': '2024-08-30T12:44:13Z', 'user': 'lx91kgr2l723wc', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 16}),
	Document(content="Question: Every time I try to git push from visual studio I keep getting this error message and I don\'t know how to fix it, I am typing my password in correctly but it tells me it no longer supports password authentication Answer: I think you need to generate security tokens instead of using passwords. Please refer to Github Webpage for more information. After you have the token, use the token for the password prompt.", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'git push error message', 'timestamp': '2024-08-30T01:18:11Z', 'user': 'm010d4pbs3d1nu', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 16}),
	Document(content="Question: Is the grade on our homework assignments based solely on the test cases shown inside of the given file or are there also hidden test cases that are looking to break the program like in CS 159? Answer: There will be more test cases when grading.¬†", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Test Cases for Homework 1', 'timestamp': '2024-08-29T21:04:18Z', 'user': 'lx92gseaaah5dy', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 127}),
	Document(content="Question: Is there a limit for the run time of our programs? For example, if a task could be completed within O(n), would we be penalized if our programs complete the task in O(n^3)? Answer: In ECE asymptotic complexities are taught in ECE36800 which is not a pre/corequisite to this course. I think that as long as your program runs to completion in under a few minutes you will not encounter any issues.", meta={'folders': ['hw1', 'other'], 'title': 'Is there a time limit for homework?', 'timestamp': '2024-08-29T18:52:18Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 138}),
	Document(content="Question: Will there be practice exams posted for us to study with? Answer: Here a few past practice/real exams I found:https://engineering.purdue.edu/~milind/ece20875/2019fall/midterm1-sol.pdfhttps://www.davidinouye.com/course/ece20875-spring-2021/docs/Exam_1_practice.pdf", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Practice Exams', 'timestamp': '2024-08-29T16:45:19Z', 'user': 'll2hlufiw3sv7', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 5, 'views': 146}),
	Document(content="Question: For the second problem on homework two, I simply just created my own list containing the triangular numbers given by the provided link on the homework. I was just wondering if that is an ok way of doing it or if there is another way that it needs to be done to receive full points. Answer: When the final homework is submitted, your program will likely be put through multiple test scenarios that weren\'t in the file, which could ask for anything, even triangle numbers up to 10,000. Hardcoding the answers will almost certainly fail those tests. Also, it goes against the point of the exercise, so it might be marked down anyways.", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Can we import own list', 'timestamp': '2024-08-29T15:37:27Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 129}),
	Document(content="Question: when I run my program, I got this result. How can I make the elements are shown as integers like the example? Answer: As mentioned in the README this link will give you useful information about typecasting. https://www.w3schools.com/python/python_casting.asp", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'HW2 list element\'s type', 'timestamp': '2024-08-28T21:30:15Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 139}),
	Document(content="Question: Hello, I am trying to test the cases on Homework 1 using Visual Studio, but when I hit \'run\', I am told that \'null\' is not defined, yet I never used the word \'null\' in any of my code. This is the message:\'Traceback (most recent call last):¬† File \'c: \\Users\AJ\OneDrive - purdue.edu\Desktop\Homework 1.ipynb\', line 5, in <module>¬† ¬† \'execution_count\': null,¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬†^^^^NameError: name \'null\' is not definedPS C: \\Users\AJ\OneDrive - purdue.edu\Desktop>\'If someone could help, that would be great. Thank you. Answer: I think this happens when there\'s an empty cell in the jupyter notebook. Try deleting the empty cell and running again", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Trying to Run Homework 1, \'null\' is not Defined', 'timestamp': '2024-08-28T14:20:36Z', 'user': 'm013fhxlz6a75q', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 140}),
	Document(content="Question: In CS159, and in other coding classes that I\'ve taken, there has normally been sort of \'comment requirement\' for our code submission. Does anything exist like that in this class? I finished my code for Homework 1 and added some comments in, however I was curious as to whether there is or is not a specific amount. Answer: no - there is no requirement for comments.¬†", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Comments on Code', 'timestamp': '2024-08-27T23:13:10Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 17}),
